questions.question: Which African country is currently home to the most number of refugees?
questions.answer_full:
The correct answer is Ethiopia.
According to the UN Refugee Agency (UNHCR), in 2015 Ethiopia was home to an estimated 736,086 refugees. Other African countries with large refugee populations include: Kenya (553,912), Uganda (477,187), the Democratic Republic of Congo (383,095) and Chad (369,540). By comparison, South Africa is home to an estimated 121,645 refugees.
Read more about asylum-seekers in South Africa here.
What's the difference between a migrant and a refugee? Read our handy definitions guide here.
*Source: UNHCR Global Trends Forced Displacement in 2015

questions.question: In 2015 Germany reported that it received over 1.1-million asylum seekers. How many applications for asylum did South Africa receive in the same year?
questions.answer_full:
The correct answer is 62,159
In 2015 South Africa received 62,159 applications for asylum. Of these applications 2,499 were approved and 58,141 (95.88%) were denied. 14,093 of the rejected applications were appealed, of which 12,361 cases are still open.
Read more:
What is the difference between a refugee and a migrant? Read our handy definition guide here.
Are there 1-million unresolved asylum cases in South Africa? The numbers don't add up.
Source: 2015 asylum statistics presentation to portfolio committee on home affairs

questions.question: The 2016 Community Survey estimates South Africa's current population at 55.7-million people. What percentage of the population was born outside of the country?
questions.answer_full:
The correct answer is 2.8% of the population
According to the most recent population survey (the 2016 Community Survey), foreign-born residents make up 2.8% of South Africa's population - or a total of 1.6-million people. This figure shows a marked decline since Census 2011, where 2.2-million people (or 4.4% of the population) indicated they were foreign-born.
Source: StatsSA Community Survey 2016
Read more: How many international migrants are there in SA?

questions.question: Gauteng province in South Africa is home to the largest numbers of both international and domestic migrants. What percentage of Gauteng residents currently living there were born outside the province?
questions.answer_full:
The correct answer is 35%
According to the latest Community Survey, 35% of the 13,399,724 people currently living in Gauteng were not born in the province. This includes domestic migrants (people who were born in South Africa, but in another province), who make up 29% of the province's population. Foreign-born residents make up 6% of Gauteng, the largest proportion of foreign-born people in any South African province.
Only 65% of people currently living in Gauteng were actually born in the province.
Read more on domestic migration in South Africa
Source: StatsSA Community Survey 2016

questions.question: Including visitors and migrants, how many foreign nationals travelled into South Africa during 2014?
questions.answer_full:
The correct answer is 15,427,689

According to the 2016 Green Paper on International Migration, during 2014 there were 15,427,689 international movements recorded at official points of entry into South Africa. This figure includes visitors and migrants. Travellers from Lesotho, Zimbabwe, Mozambique, Swaziland and Botswana made up 74% of all recorded arrivals.

Read more:

Green Paper on International Migration

Report: The geography of migration

questions.question: Which of the following countries sent the most number of visitors to South Africa by road (in April 2016)?
questions.answer_full:
The correct answer is Pakistan*
In April 2016, South African border posts recorded 521 road arrivals for nationals of Pakistan -  accounting for nearly a third of all arrivals from Pakistan for that time period.
Each year some 80% of all foreign arrivals into South Africa are by road. In the April 2016 tourism and migration report StatsSA said that road transport was used by 2,515,757 (72,6%) of the 3,465,092 documented international (non-South African) travellers. Air transport air transport was used by 933,066 (26,9%) of these people, with only 16 269 (0,5%) of foreigners arriving by sea.
Read more: The geography of international migration in South Africa
* Source: StatsSA tourism and migration report for April 2016

questions.question: The majority of foreign visitors and migrants who enter South Africa come from other African countries. What percentage of these travellers come to South Africa in order to study?
questions.answer_full:
Answer: 25.4% of temporary residence permits for African nationals are issued to international students
According to Statistic South Africa's report on documented immigration in 2014, only 18.7% of temporary residence permits granted to African citizens were for the purposes of work. More than a quarter (25.4%) of temporary residence permits were for international students. 30.3% of permits issued to African nationals are visitors' permits.
When all overseas nationals are included, the proportion shifts: in 2014 work permits made up 34.6% of all temporary permits that were issued, followed by visitors' permits (31.3%) and relatives permits (21.2%).
Read more about the types of residence visas and permits South Africa offers foreign nationals, and how many permits are issued annually to which countries.

questions.question: Between 2014 and 2015, 1,955 couples applied for permanent residence (for one partner) on the basis of a marriage or similar recognised partnership* - the so-called "spousal visa". What percentage of these applications investigated by the department of home affairs? inspectorate were rejected?
questions.answer_full:
A. 74% of spousal visa applications were rejected
Incredibly, the department of home affairs' inspectorate found just 24% of the marriages it investigated were credible - and rejected 74% of the applications for a spousal visa "on the basis that the marriage was found to be fraudulent".
Source: Green Paper on International Migration
Read more about what types of South African visas and permits are granted to foreign nationals here.
*this includes long-term or "common law" partnerships and same sex marriages

questions.question: Which of the following countries provides the most medical practitioners, medical specialists, dentists and pharmacists to South Africa's public health services?
questions.answer_full:
The correct answer is the Democratic Republic of the Congo
According to a 2015 study by the Migrating for Work Research Consortium (MiWORC), looking at data from the South African Department of Health, the top 10 countries for foreign citizenship of medical practitioners, medical specialists, dentists and pharmacists included the DRC (490 practioners), Nigeria (380), Cuba (150), India (150), Zimbabwe (140) and the United Kingdom (130).
Source: MiWORC paper on "Foreign health professionals in the South African public service", October 2015.
Read more about foreign-born migrants and employment in South Africa here.

questions.question: How many refugee children currently access foster child grants from the South African Social Services Agency (SASSA)?
questions.answer_full:
The correct answer is 28
According to data from SASSA, by the end of March 2016 there were a total of 44,552 foreign-born migrant children receiving child grants from the state (including those with permanent resident status and refugee status). Of this total, 28 refugee children and 629 (foreign-born) permanent resident children received foster child grants.
Are "vast numbers" of refugee and foreign-born migrant children forced to rely on South African social services grants? Available data does not support this claim. Read our report here.
